04213nam a22005415i 9780773554276DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735542767 a10.1515/97807735542762doi  a(DE-B1597)657614  a(OCoLC)1030892958  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQL84.24b.F57 2018eb 7aNAT0390002bisacsh04a333.95/41609712231 aForan, Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Subjugation of Canadian Wildlife :bFailures of Principle and Policy /cMax Foran. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b1 diagram  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Rural, Wildland, and Resource Studies ;v900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Trajectory of a Belief System -- tManaging Wildlife under the Belief System -- tWildlife Policies -- tManaging Apex Predators -- tManaging Other Wildlife -- tConservation of Species and their Habitats -- tThe Species at Risk Act -- tThreats to Terrestrial and Marine Habitats -- tProtected Areas -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHardly a day goes by without news of the extinction or endangerment of yet another animal species, followed by urgent but largely unheeded calls for action. An eloquent denunciation of the failures of Canada's government and society to protect wildlife from human exploitation, Max Foran's The Subjugation of Canadian Wildlife argues that a root cause of wildlife depletions and habitat loss is the culturally ingrained beliefs that underpin management practices and policies. Tracing the evolution of the highly contestable assumptions that define the human–wildlife relationship, Foran stresses the price wild animals pay for human self-interest. Using several examples of government oversight at the federal, provincial, and territorial levels, from the Species at Risk Act to the Biodiversity Strategy, Protected Areas Network, and provincial management plans, this volume shows that wildlife policies are as much – or more – about human needs, priorities, and profit as they are about preservation. Challenging established concepts including ecological integrity, adaptive management, sport hunting as conservation, and the flawed belief that wildlife is a renewable resource, the author compels us to recognize animals as sentient individuals and as integral components of complex ecological systems. A passionate critique of contemporary wildlife policy, The Subjugation of Canadian Wildlife calls for belief-change as the best hope for an ecologically healthy, wildlife-rich Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWildlife conservationxGovernment policyzCanada. 0aWildlife managementxGovernment policyzCanada. 7aNATURE / Animal Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355427640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773554276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773554276/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles